Here are clear, exam-ready notes on Time Complexity and Space Complexity in Python, written in a simple and structured way 👇

📘 TIME COMPLEXITY (Python)
🔹 What is Time Complexity?

Time complexity measures how fast an algorithm runs based on input size n.

It tells how the execution time grows when input increases.

🔹 Common Time Complexities
Complexity	Name	Example
O(1)	Constant	Access element
O(log n)	Logarithmic	Binary Search
O(n)	Linear	Loop
O(n log n)	Linear Log	Merge Sort
O(n²)	Quadratic	Nested loops
O(2ⁿ)	Exponential	Recursion (subset)
🔹 Python Examples
✅ O(1) – Constant Time
arr = [1, 2, 3, 4]
print(arr[2])   # direct access
✅ O(n) – Linear Time
for i in range(n):
    print(i)
✅ O(n²) – Quadratic Time
for i in range(n):
    for j in range(n):
        print(i, j)
✅ O(log n) – Logarithmic (Binary Search)
def binary_search(arr, target):
    left, right = 0, len(arr)-1
    while left <= right:
        mid = (left + right)//2
        if arr[mid] == target:
            return mid
        elif arr[mid] < target:
            left = mid + 1
        else:
            right = mid - 1
🔹 Rules to Calculate Time Complexity
Single loop → O(n)
Nested loops → O(n²)
Divide problem → O(log n)

Ignore constants

O(2n + 5) → O(n)
Keep worst case
📘 SPACE COMPLEXITY (Python)
🔹 What is Space Complexity?

Space complexity measures how much memory an algorithm uses.

Includes:

Variables
Data structures
Recursion stack
🔹 Types of Space
1. Input Space

Memory used by input

2. Auxiliary Space

Extra memory used (important for exams)

🔹 Python Examples
✅ O(1) – Constant Space
a = 10
b = 20
c = a + b
✅ O(n) – Linear Space
arr = []
for i in range(n):
    arr.append(i)
✅ O(n) – Recursion Stack
def func(n):
    if n == 0:
        return
    func(n-1)
🔹 Key Points
List/Array of size n → O(n) space
Recursion depth n → O(n) space
Variables → usually O(1)
📘 TIME vs SPACE TRADE-OFF

Sometimes:

Faster code uses more memory
Less memory uses more time

Example:

# Faster (uses extra space)
seen = set(arr)

# Slower (no extra space)
for i in range(len(arr)):
    for j in range(i+1, len(arr)):
        pass
📘 QUICK SUMMARY
Time complexity → speed
Space complexity → memory
Always aim for:
Lower time
Optimized space
📘 INTERVIEW TIPS

✔ Always mention:

Best case
Worst case
Space used

✔ Focus on:

Arrays
Strings
Hashmaps (dict, set)
Recursion
